fields.name: global.compression
fields.summary: Whether the client connection uses compression in the client/server protocol.

fields.name: global.connection_errors_accept
fields.summary: The number of errors that occurred during calls to accept() on the listening port.

fields.name: global.connection_errors_internal
fields.summary: The number of connections refused due to internal errors in the server, such as failure to start a new thread or an out-of-memory condition.

fields.name: global.connection_errors_max_connections
fields.summary: The number of connections refused because the server max_connections limit was reached.

fields.name: global.connection_errors_peer_address
fields.summary: The number of errors that occurred while searching for connecting client IP addresses.

fields.name: global.connection_errors_select
fields.summary: The number of errors that occurred during calls to select() or poll() on the listening port. (Failure of this operation does not necessarily means a client connection was rejected.)

fields.name: global.connection_errors_tcpwrap
fields.summary: The number of connections refused by the libwrap library.

fields.name: global.connections
fields.summary: The number of connection attempts (successful or not) to the MySQL server.

fields.name: global.created_tmp_disk_tables
fields.summary: The total number of temporary tables that were converted to disk based tables, due to exceeding either tmp_table_size or max_heap_table_size.

fields.name: global.created_tmp_files
fields.summary: How many temporary files mysqld has created.

fields.name: global.created_tmp_tables
fields.summary: The total number of temporary tables created.

fields.name: global.current_tls_ca
fields.summary: The active ssl_ca value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This context value may differ from the current ssl_ca system variable value if the system variable has been changed but ALTER INSTANCE RELOAD TLS has not subsequently been executed to reconfigure the SSL context from the context-related system variable values and update the corresponding status variables. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_capath
fields.summary: The active ssl_capath value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_cert
fields.summary: The active ssl_cert value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_cipher
fields.summary: The active ssl_cipher value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_ciphersuites
fields.summary: The active tls_ciphersuites value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_crl
fields.summary: The active ssl_crl value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_crlpath
fields.summary: The active ssl_crlpath value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_key
fields.summary: The active ssl_key value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.current_tls_version
fields.summary: The active tls_version value in the SSL context that the server uses for new connections. This variable was added in MySQL 8.0.16.

fields.name: global.delayed_errors
fields.summary: The number of rows written with INSERT DELAYED for which some error occurred (probably duplicate key). This status variable is deprecated (because DELAYED inserts are deprecated), and will be removed in a future release.

fields.name: global.delayed_insert_threads
fields.summary: The number of INSERT DELAYED handler threads in use for nontransactional tables. This status variable is deprecated (because DELAYED inserts are deprecated), and will be removed in a future release.

fields.name: global.delayed_writes
fields.summary: The number of INSERT DELAYED rows written to nontransactional tables. This status variable is deprecated (because DELAYED inserts are deprecated), and will be removed in a future release.

fields.name: global.flush_commands
fields.summary: The number of executed FLUSH statements.

fields.name: global.handler_commit
fields.summary: The number of internal COMMIT statements.

fields.name: global.handler_delete
fields.summary: The number of times that rows have been deleted from tables.

fields.name: global.handler_discover
fields.summary: The MySQL server can ask the NDBCLUSTER storage engine if it knows about a table with a given name. This is called discovery. Handler_discover indicates the number of times that tables have been discovered using this mechanism.

fields.name: global.handler_external_lock
fields.summary: The server increments this variable for each call to its external_lock() function, which generally occurs at the beginning and end of access to a table instance.

fields.name: global.handler_mrr_init
fields.summary: The number of times the server uses a storage engine's own Multi-Range Read implementation for table access.

fields.name: global.handler_prepare
fields.summary: A counter for the prepare phase of two-phase commit operations.

fields.name: global.handler_read_first
fields.summary: The number of times the first entry in an index was read. If this value is high, it suggests that the server is doing a lot of full index scans; for example, SELECT col1 FROM foo, assuming that col1 is indexed.

fields.name: global.handler_read_key
fields.summary: The number of requests to read the last key in an index. If this value is high, it is a good indication that your tables are properly indexed for your queries.

fields.name: global.handler_read_last
fields.summary: The number of requests to read the last key in an index. With ORDER BY, the server will issue a first-key request followed by several next-key requests, whereas with With ORDER BY DESC, the server will issue a last-key request followed by several previous-key requests. This variable was added in MySQL 5.6.1.

fields.name: global.handler_read_next
fields.summary: The number of requests to read the next row in key order. This value is incremented if you are querying an index column with a range constraint or if you are doing an index scan.

fields.name: global.handler_read_prev
fields.summary: The number of requests to read the previous row in key order. This read method is mainly used to optimize ORDER BY ... DESC.

fields.name: global.handler_read_rnd
fields.summary: The number of requests to read a row based on a fixed position. This value is high if you are doing a lot of queries that require sorting of the result. You probably have a lot of queries that require MySQL to scan entire tables or you have joins that do not use keys properly.

fields.name: global.handler_read_rnd_next
fields.summary: The number of requests to read the next row in the data file. This value is high if you are doing a lot of table scans. Generally this suggests that your tables are not properly indexed or that your queries are not written to take advantage of the indexes you have.

fields.name: global.handler_rollback
fields.summary: The number of requests for a storage engine to perform a rollback operation.

fields.name: global.handler_savepoint
fields.summary: The number of requests for a storage engine to place a savepoint.

fields.name: global.handler_savepoint_rollback
fields.summary: The number of requests for a storage engine to rollback to a savepoint.

fields.name: global.handler_update
fields.summary: The number of requests to update a row in a table.

fields.name: global.handler_write
fields.summary: The number of requests to insert a row in a table.

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_bytes_data
fields.summary: Buffer bytes containing data (innodb_buffer_pool_bytes_data)

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_bytes_dirty
fields.summary: Buffer bytes currently dirty (innodb_buffer_pool_bytes_dirty)

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_dump_status
fields.summary: The progress of an operation to record the pages held in the InnoDB buffer pool, triggered by the setting of innodb_buffer_pool_dump_at_shutdown or innodb_buffer_pool_dump_now.

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_load_status
fields.summary: The progress of an operation to warm up the InnoDB buffer pool by reading in a set of pages corresponding to an earlier point in time, triggered by the setting of innodb_buffer_pool_load_at_startup or innodb_buffer_pool_load_now.

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_pages_data
fields.summary: Buffer pages containing data (innodb_buffer_pool_pages_data)

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_pages_dirty
fields.summary: Buffer pages currently dirty (innodb_buffer_pool_pages_dirty)

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_pages_flushed
fields.summary: The number of requests to flush pages from the InnoDB buffer pool.

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_pages_free
fields.summary: Buffer pages currently free (innodb_buffer_pool_pages_free)

fields.name: global.innodb_buffer_pool_pages_misc

fields.name: global.tc_log_max_pages_used
fields.summary: For the memory-mapped implementation of the log that is used by mysqld when it acts as the transaction coordinator for recovery of internal XA transactions, this variable indicates the largest number of pages used for the log since the server started. If the product of Tc_log_max_pages_used and Tc_log_page_size is always significantly less than the log size, the size is larger than necessary and can be reduced. (The size is set by the --log-tc-size option. This variable is unused: It is unneeded for binary log-based recovery, and the memory-mapped recovery log method is not used unless the number of storage engines that are capable of two-phase commit and that support XA transactions is greater than one. (InnoDB is the only applicable engine.)

fields.name: global.tc_log_page_waits
fields.summary: For the memory-mapped implementation of the recovery log, this variable increments each time the server was not able to commit a transaction and had to wait for a free page in the log. If this value is large, you might want to increase the log size (with the --log-tc-size option). For binary log-based recovery, this variable increments each time the binary log cannot be closed because there are two-phase commits in progress. (The close operation waits until all such transactions are finished.)

fields.name: global.threads_cached

fields.name: global.threads_connected

fields.name: global.threads_running

fields.name: global.uptime

fields.name: global.uptime_since_flush_status
fields.summary: The number of seconds since the most recent FLUSH STATUS statement.
